[2
Date: 3 Sep 1999
From: Laura E. Robinson <Laura.Robinson@tdh.state.tx.us>
Willacy County has a local rabies control authority/animal control officer
who is responsible for investigating animal bites and possible rabies
exposures. In this particular county, the suspected rabid animals are
taken to either of 2 local veterinarians for euthanasia and head removal.
The animal specimens are shipped by bus to the Texas Department of
Health's (TDH) Rabies Laboratory in Austin for testing by direct
immunofluorescence. Positive specimens are also tested by monoclonal
antibody and PCR techniques to determine the rabies virus strain.
When an animal tests positive for rabies in Texas, the incident is
investigated by the Zoonosis Control Division of the Texas Department of
Health in collaboration with local animal control and health department
authorities. Human and animal exposures are evaluated using TDH guidelines
(Rabies Prevention in Texas - 1997, available at the Zoonosis website:
www.tdh.state.tx.us/zoonosis/), which follow the Advisory Committee on
Immunization Practices (ACIP) "Human Rabies Prevention - United States
1999" guidelines published by Centers for Disease Control (CDC)
. In Texas, we follow the standard rabies
postexposure treatment regimen: Human Rabies Immuno Globulin (HRIG) plus
tissue culture vaccine on day 0, and additional vaccine doses on day 3, 7,
14, and 28.
--
Laura E. Robinson, DVM, MS
Zoonosis Control Veterinarian
Texas Department of Health - Region 11
Harlingen, Texas 78550
e-mail: Laura.Robinson@tdh.state.tx.us
visit www.tdh.state.tx.us/zoonosis
